1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074
Subtitle downloaded with
Sublight (www.sublight.me)

2
00:00:57,504 --> 00:01:02,601
11:55. Almost midnight.

3
00:01:02,642 --> 00:01:06,237
Enough time for one more story.

4
00:01:06,279 --> 00:01:11,274
One more story
before 12:00...

5
00:01:11,319 --> 00:01:13,753
just to keep us warm.

6
00:01:15,456 --> 00:01:21,725
In five minutes,
it will be the 21st of April.

7
00:01:21,763 --> 00:01:26,996
One hundred years ago,
on the 21st of April...

8
00:01:27,034 --> 00:01:30,937
out on the waters
around Spivey Point...

9
00:01:30,973 --> 00:01:35,706
a small clipper ship
drew toward land.

10
00:01:35,744 --> 00:01:40,443
Suddenly, out of the night,
the fog rolled in.

11
00:01:40,482 --> 00:01:43,451
For a moment,
they could see nothing...

12
00:01:43,485 --> 00:01:45,953
not a foot ahead of them.

13
00:01:45,988 --> 00:01:49,686
Then they saw a light.

14
00:01:49,726 --> 00:01:55,187
By God, it was a fire
burning on the shore...

15
00:01:55,231 --> 00:01:59,759
strong enough to penetrate
the swirling mist.

16
00:01:59,803 --> 00:02:04,240
They steered a course
toward the light...

17
00:02:04,274 --> 00:02:08,472
but it was a campfire
like this one.

18
00:02:08,511 --> 00:02:12,915
The ship crashed
against the rocks.

19
00:02:12,950 --> 00:02:15,248
The hull sheared in two.

20
00:02:15,286 --> 00:02:18,255
The mast snapped like a twig...

21
00:02:18,289 --> 00:02:23,283
and the wreckage sank
with all the men aboard.

22
00:02:24,795 --> 00:02:26,922
At the bottom of the sea...

23
00:02:26,964 --> 00:02:30,765
lay the ''Elizabeth Dane''
with her crew...

24
00:02:30,802 --> 00:02:34,260
their lungs
filled with salt water...

25
00:02:34,306 --> 00:02:38,936
their eyes open
and staring into the darkness.

26
00:02:38,977 --> 00:02:42,936
And above,
as suddenly as it had come...

27
00:02:42,981 --> 00:02:44,778
the fog lifted...

28
00:02:44,816 --> 00:02:47,614
receded
back across the ocean...

29
00:02:47,652 --> 00:02:50,315
and never came again.

30
00:02:50,356 --> 00:02:53,621
But it is told
by the fishermen...

31
00:02:53,659 --> 00:02:56,628
and their fathers
and grandfathers...

32
00:02:56,662 --> 00:03:01,065
that when the fog returns
to Antonio Bay...

33
00:03:01,100 --> 00:03:05,059
the men
at the bottom of the sea...

34
00:03:05,104 --> 00:03:08,562
out in the water
by Spivey Point...

35
00:03:08,608 --> 00:03:13,478
will rise up
and search for the campfire...

36
00:03:13,514 --> 00:03:20,010
that led them
to their dark and icy death.

37
00:03:22,389 --> 00:03:28,294
Twelve o' clock,
the 21st of April.

38
00:04:22,786 --> 00:04:24,413
It's twelve midnight...

39
00:04:24,454 --> 00:04:26,820
and we just started
into the witching hour.

40
00:04:26,856 --> 00:04:30,223
This is Stevie Wayne,
on top of the world tonight.

41
00:04:30,260 --> 00:04:33,628
And I'll be here
right up until about 1:00.

42
00:05:00,859 --> 00:05:03,293
I'm all through, Father.

43
00:05:03,328 --> 00:05:06,024
Oh, thank you, Bennett.

44
00:05:06,064 --> 00:05:10,797
I won't need you
until four tomorrow, Bennett.

45
00:05:10,836 --> 00:05:12,168
Yes, sir.

46
00:05:13,473 --> 00:05:16,408
Would you like something to
keep you warm on the way home?

47
00:05:16,442 --> 00:05:19,411
No, thank you.
Father, can I get paid?

48
00:05:21,681 --> 00:05:27,483
Why don't you come in at six
instead of four tomorrow?

49
00:05:27,520 --> 00:05:29,681
Yes, sir.

50
00:05:39,933 --> 00:05:41,833
Bennett?

51
00:06:57,048 --> 00:06:58,777
It's 59 degrees outside.

52
00:06:58,816 --> 00:07:01,546
And let me be the first
to wish Antonio Bay...

53
00:07:01,586 --> 00:07:03,053
a happy birthday.

54
00:07:03,087 --> 00:07:06,614
We're one hundred years old
today.

55
00:07:06,657 --> 00:07:08,887
The weatherman's
been trying to spoil it for us.

56
00:07:08,926 --> 00:07:11,019
He says we may be
in for some rain tonight.

57
00:07:11,062 --> 00:07:15,261
But from where I'm sitting,
it looks like clear skies.

58
00:07:15,300 --> 00:07:18,098
I think the weatherman's
been working too hard.

59
00:07:18,137 --> 00:07:20,071
Well, I'll stay here
for another hour...

60
00:07:20,105 --> 00:07:22,403
just to see if he's right.

61
00:07:22,441 --> 00:07:24,966
And I'm inviting you
to stay here with me.

62
00:07:26,111 --> 00:07:30,275
There's a cutter run aground
over here on the east bay, over.

63
00:07:31,517 --> 00:07:35,750
Global 1X5.
It's the ''Lady Belle Pacific.''

64
00:07:35,789 --> 00:07:39,987
Serial number 024KL596. Over.

65
00:07:40,026 --> 00:07:42,426
Global 1X5,
the ''Lady Belle Pacific''...

66
00:07:42,462 --> 00:07:44,487
is seaworthy, no major damage.

67
00:07:44,531 --> 00:07:46,089
Why don't you
send a tow on over here...

68
00:07:46,132 --> 00:07:49,124
about a quarter mile
above the Boatel. Over.

69
00:11:46,251 --> 00:11:50,847
This is KAB,
Antonio Bay, California.

70
00:11:52,190 --> 00:11:55,216
Six minutes after midnight.

71
00:11:55,260 --> 00:11:56,488
Haven't heard
from the weatherman yet...

72
00:11:56,528 --> 00:11:58,997
so I can't say for sure
about that rain...

73
00:11:59,031 --> 00:12:03,127
but there's a full moon
and no clouds in the sky.

74
00:12:04,637 --> 00:12:06,127
I'm Stevie Wayne.

75
00:12:06,172 --> 00:12:08,606
And if you don't have anything
to do right now...

76
00:12:08,641 --> 00:12:12,634
I'll be here playing music
all through the witching hour.

77
00:12:16,515 --> 00:12:18,609
Even if you do
have something to do...

78
00:12:18,652 --> 00:12:20,779
keep me turned on for a while...

79
00:12:20,821 --> 00:12:23,619
and I'll try my best
to do the same for you.

80
00:12:23,657 --> 00:12:24,851
OK!

81
00:12:46,447 --> 00:12:48,972
-How far you going?
-Other side of town.

82
00:12:49,016 --> 00:12:50,347
That's close enough.

83
00:12:52,186 --> 00:12:55,019
-Make it?
-Yeah. Thank you.

84
00:13:05,467 --> 00:13:07,196
Sip?

85
00:13:07,236 --> 00:13:08,726
Thanks.

86
00:13:15,310 --> 00:13:18,371
Listen,
I never hitchhiked before.

87
00:13:18,414 --> 00:13:20,507
I just really want
to be careful.

88
00:13:20,550 --> 00:13:22,450
-Can I ask you something?
-Sure.

89
00:13:22,485 --> 00:13:24,976
Are you weird?

90
00:13:25,021 --> 00:13:27,182
Yes, I am.

91
00:13:27,223 --> 00:13:29,214
Yes, I am weird.

92
00:13:29,259 --> 00:13:31,784
You are weird.
Thank God you're weird.

93
00:13:31,828 --> 00:13:34,661
The last one was so normal,
it was disgusting.

94
00:13:34,697 --> 00:13:36,494
He picked me up
in Santa Barbara.

95
00:13:36,533 --> 00:13:38,695
By the time we got to Carmel
he wanted to marry me.

96
00:13:38,736 --> 00:13:41,398
Oh, yeah. I thought
you never hitchhiked before.

97
00:13:45,543 --> 00:13:47,534
Not before last week.

98
00:13:47,578 --> 00:13:50,445
You're my...

99
00:13:50,481 --> 00:13:52,039
thirteenth ride.

100
00:13:52,082 --> 00:13:54,812
Oh, great. Weird and unlucky.

101
00:13:54,852 --> 00:13:57,480
We'll see.

102
00:14:00,559 --> 00:14:01,753
Look out!

103
00:14:08,733 --> 00:14:09,995
-Are you all right?
-I'm fine.

104
00:14:10,035 --> 00:14:12,265
-You're sure?
-I think so.

105
00:14:12,304 --> 00:14:13,862
What the hell was--

106
00:14:20,346 --> 00:14:22,541
It's exactly twelve minutes
after midnight...

107
00:14:22,582 --> 00:14:24,447
and this is Stevie Wayne.

108
00:14:24,483 --> 00:14:26,314
Let's get out of here.

109
00:14:28,554 --> 00:14:31,387
I'm high tonight in the KAB
lighthouse on Spivey Point.

110
00:14:31,424 --> 00:14:33,949
And in case you've forgotten,
it's April 21st...

111
00:14:33,993 --> 00:14:36,223
and a happy birthday
for Antonio Bay.

112
00:14:36,262 --> 00:14:39,129
Now, there's a celebration
planned for tonight.

113
00:14:39,165 --> 00:14:42,966
So if you're so excited
about it you can't sleep...

114
00:14:43,003 --> 00:14:45,597
well, stay up with me...

115
00:14:45,639 --> 00:14:50,941
and I'll figure out some way
to keep you occupied.

116
00:14:50,978 --> 00:14:52,138
Or not.

117
00:14:57,751 --> 00:14:59,652
-KAB.
-Hi, sweetheart.

118
00:14:59,687 --> 00:15:01,848
Hi, Dan. What have you got?

119
00:15:01,889 --> 00:15:03,754
Well, I'm just calling
to see if you're lonely...

120
00:15:03,791 --> 00:15:05,019
if there's anything
I can do about it.

121
00:15:05,059 --> 00:15:06,788
Never lonely, Dan.

122
00:15:06,828 --> 00:15:08,090
I thought
you were off work at 8:00.

123
00:15:08,129 --> 00:15:10,529
I changed shifts to make it
to the big party tonight.

124
00:15:10,565 --> 00:15:11,691
Will you be there?

125
00:15:11,733 --> 00:15:15,191
Until I can talk someone else...

126
00:15:15,236 --> 00:15:18,467
into giving up city life
for Antonio Bay, I'm it.

127
00:15:18,506 --> 00:15:21,476
-And ''it'' means day and night.
-Too much work.

128
00:15:21,510 --> 00:15:23,478
That's what I get
for owning a station.

129
00:15:23,512 --> 00:15:24,604
And if you don't tell me
why you called...

130
00:15:24,647 --> 00:15:26,945
in about fifteen seconds,
I'll have to hang up on you.

131
00:15:26,982 --> 00:15:29,450
-Want something to talk about?
-Anything.

132
00:15:29,485 --> 00:15:31,885
I've got a position
on a trawler about...

133
00:15:31,920 --> 00:15:35,583
fifteen miles out
called the ''Sea Grass.''

134
00:15:35,624 --> 00:15:37,182
And I've got
something on my scope--

135
00:15:37,226 --> 00:15:39,126
appears to be a fog bank.

136
00:15:39,161 --> 00:15:42,495
It's about 25 miles out,
moving in their direction.

137
00:15:42,532 --> 00:15:46,263
Thanks, Dan.
That's worth about ten seconds.

138
00:15:46,303 --> 00:15:48,328
I'm on the air. Bye.

139
00:15:53,143 --> 00:15:54,667
Ahoy, maties.

140
00:15:54,711 --> 00:15:57,578
This is KAB, Antonio Bay.

141
00:15:57,614 --> 00:16:01,483
Stevie Wayne here
beaming a signal across the sea.

142
00:16:01,519 --> 00:16:04,750
To the men of the ''Sea Grass,''
fifteen miles out tonight...

143
00:16:04,789 --> 00:16:06,154
a warm hello...

144
00:16:06,190 --> 00:16:08,920
and keep a watch out
for that fog bank...

145
00:16:08,959 --> 00:16:10,756
heading in from the east.

146
00:16:10,795 --> 00:16:12,262
Now, in the meantime...

147
00:16:12,296 --> 00:16:14,924
relax with me
while I play this song...

148
00:16:14,965 --> 00:16:18,594
from the Coupe DeVilles,
dedicated just to you.

149
00:16:18,636 --> 00:16:21,333
Boy, would I like to meet her.

150
00:16:21,373 --> 00:16:22,601
I saw her
at a grocery store one day.

151
00:16:22,641 --> 00:16:24,609
-And?
-You would like to meet her.

152
00:16:24,643 --> 00:16:27,612
She's crazy.
There's no fog bank out there.

153
00:16:27,646 --> 00:16:29,113
What do you know about her?

154
00:16:29,147 --> 00:16:31,479
-She owns that lighthouse.
-I know that.

155
00:16:31,516 --> 00:16:33,279
Her son plays Little League
with my kid brother.

156
00:16:33,318 --> 00:16:34,615
She's a mother?

157
00:16:34,653 --> 00:16:36,280
I thought
you were happily married.

158
00:16:36,321 --> 00:16:37,948
Not that happy.

159
00:16:37,989 --> 00:16:40,787
No fog bank out there.

160
00:16:48,368 --> 00:16:50,336
There's a fog bank out there.

161
00:16:52,171 --> 00:16:55,197
All right. I'm drunk enough.

162
00:16:55,241 --> 00:16:57,175
Let's go back.

163
00:16:57,210 --> 00:16:59,041
All right, all right.

164
00:17:03,217 --> 00:17:05,708
Al, come here.

165
00:17:05,753 --> 00:17:08,051
-Just give him a hand.
-Come here.

166
00:17:20,300 --> 00:17:22,394
What was that?

167
00:17:50,099 --> 00:17:52,158
Come here.

168
00:17:54,670 --> 00:17:56,661
What was that?

169
00:18:05,282 --> 00:18:06,943
It's the generator.

170
00:18:08,285 --> 00:18:10,378
Wha--wha...

171
00:18:14,491 --> 00:18:15,753
Al.

172
00:18:32,143 --> 00:18:33,701
It's gone.

173
00:18:33,744 --> 00:18:35,609
There was just a ship out there.

174
00:18:35,646 --> 00:18:37,273
Al, listen.

175
00:18:37,315 --> 00:18:39,442
Nothing.

176
00:18:39,484 --> 00:18:41,645
-Listen.
-Who's there?

177
00:18:52,831 --> 00:18:54,890
Who is that?

178
00:19:43,752 --> 00:19:45,481
Al, it's right beside us.

179
00:19:48,423 --> 00:19:52,154
It's big, Al. It's a ship.

180
00:19:52,193 --> 00:19:53,956
It's a big ship!

181
00:19:57,666 --> 00:19:59,463
What happened?
Did you get wet?

182
00:20:18,688 --> 00:20:21,486
It's 12:43...

183
00:20:21,524 --> 00:20:23,890
and I've got
four in a row for you...

184
00:20:23,926 --> 00:20:26,191
right here on KAB.

185
00:21:02,800 --> 00:21:05,167
Nothing but water, Stevie.

186
00:21:08,040 --> 00:21:10,167
But it sure beats Chicago.

187
00:21:15,681 --> 00:21:16,978
KAB.

188
00:21:17,016 --> 00:21:18,711
I like what you said...

189
00:21:18,751 --> 00:21:21,049
but for your information,
you lied.

190
00:21:21,086 --> 00:21:23,452
The fog bank
has moved due west...

191
00:21:23,489 --> 00:21:27,119
and probably
missed the ship entirely.

192
00:21:27,160 --> 00:21:28,991
Well, my gauges must be wrong.

193
00:21:29,029 --> 00:21:30,724
I've got a wind blowing
due east.

194
00:21:30,764 --> 00:21:33,324
What kind of a fog
blows against the wind?

195
00:21:33,366 --> 00:21:35,834
-You got me.
-I'm not so sure I want you.

196
00:21:35,869 --> 00:21:37,666
You're just
a voice on the phone.

197
00:21:37,704 --> 00:21:41,003
You're a voice on the radio.
We'd make a perfect couple.

198
00:21:43,009 --> 00:21:46,036
You let me take you to dinner
tonight, I'll prove it to you.

199
00:21:46,080 --> 00:21:47,980
Sorry, Dan.

200
00:21:48,015 --> 00:21:51,246
My idea of perfection
is a voice on the phone.

201
00:21:51,285 --> 00:21:53,981
OK, mystery lady.

202
00:21:54,021 --> 00:21:56,421
-Good night.
-Good night.

203
00:22:17,345 --> 00:22:18,505
Not bad.

204
00:22:20,282 --> 00:22:22,807
I started a week ago
in San Diego...

205
00:22:22,851 --> 00:22:26,253
right up the coast,
five drawings a day.

206
00:22:26,289 --> 00:22:28,086
It'll probably take me a month
to get to Vancouver...

207
00:22:28,124 --> 00:22:29,682
and if I can sell them
for five bucks apiece...

208
00:22:29,726 --> 00:22:32,024
-I'll be rich.
-Yeah.

209
00:22:34,897 --> 00:22:36,831
-Can I ask you something?
-Sure.

210
00:22:36,866 --> 00:22:38,891
What's your name?

211
00:22:38,935 --> 00:22:41,597
-Elizabeth.
-Nick.

212
00:22:41,637 --> 00:22:44,367
-Hello, Nick.
-Hi.

213
00:22:46,142 --> 00:22:48,236
Is that where you're from,
San Diego?

214
00:22:48,278 --> 00:22:50,678
Wait a minute. You said,
''Can I ask something?''

215
00:22:50,714 --> 00:22:52,909
Well, something,
to me, means one thing.

216
00:22:52,950 --> 00:22:55,612
-San Diego is two things.
-OK.

217
00:22:57,387 --> 00:23:02,347
Pasadena, and a lot of money.

218
00:23:02,392 --> 00:23:04,826
Never a chance to do
anything I want to do.

219
00:23:09,501 --> 00:23:11,696
What do you want to do?

220
00:23:11,736 --> 00:23:14,830
I don't know.

221
00:23:14,873 --> 00:23:18,070
That's OK. Me, neither.

222
00:23:18,109 --> 00:23:20,839
I think I got to have this one.
Can I buy it?

223
00:23:22,614 --> 00:23:24,172
The drawing's free.

224
00:24:21,409 --> 00:24:23,707
It's 1:00, straight up...

225
00:24:23,744 --> 00:24:27,339
the end of the witching hour,
and time for me to sign off.

226
00:24:33,655 --> 00:24:36,317
So until tomorrow night,
at 6 P.M...

227
00:24:36,358 --> 00:24:38,485
when KAB
comes back on the air...

228
00:24:38,527 --> 00:24:41,291
this is Stevie Wayne,
your night light...

229
00:24:41,330 --> 00:24:44,231
hoping you have
a nice rest of the night.

230
00:26:42,523 --> 00:26:44,252
Hey, Mom !

231
00:26:49,497 --> 00:26:52,524
Mom, come on. Get up.
Look what I found.

232
00:26:52,568 --> 00:26:57,198
Andy...I love you...

233
00:26:57,239 --> 00:26:59,673
but sometimes
you're a real pain.

234
00:26:59,708 --> 00:27:01,335
Sure, Mom, but look it.

235
00:27:01,377 --> 00:27:02,708
First, it was a gold coin.

236
00:27:02,745 --> 00:27:05,509
Then it turned into
this neat piece of wood.

237
00:27:05,547 --> 00:27:07,105
This is one of those times.

238
00:27:07,149 --> 00:27:08,844
Look at it, Mom.

239
00:27:13,056 --> 00:27:15,024
Good morning, Andrew.

240
00:27:15,058 --> 00:27:17,151
Did you have a nice time
last night?

241
00:27:17,193 --> 00:27:20,185
Yeah. Old Mr. Machen
told us ghost stories.

242
00:27:20,230 --> 00:27:22,960
Did you thank Mrs. Kobritz
for bringing you home?

243
00:27:22,999 --> 00:27:26,298
Yes, ma'am. Mom, can I have
a stomach pounder and a Coke?

244
00:27:26,336 --> 00:27:29,737
-After lunch.
-OK.

245
00:27:29,773 --> 00:27:31,469
I'm gonna go look
for another one.

246
00:27:31,509 --> 00:27:34,000
Maybe this time
I can get the gold coin.

247
00:27:58,804 --> 00:28:00,567
Where the hell is he?

248
00:28:00,605 --> 00:28:02,732
Rolled out of here
at 4:15 yesterday.

249
00:28:02,774 --> 00:28:05,140
-That's the last I saw of him.
-Al said 7:30, right here.

250
00:28:05,177 --> 00:28:07,270
You know Al.
If I were you--

251
00:28:07,312 --> 00:28:08,802
Did you call
the Coast Guard, Hank?

252
00:28:08,847 --> 00:28:10,873
Nick, they probably
got drunk last night.

253
00:28:10,917 --> 00:28:13,784
-No, he wouldn't do that.
-He'd do anything.

254
00:28:13,820 --> 00:28:16,084
Al and I got drunk so many times
I can't count them all...

255
00:28:16,122 --> 00:28:19,421
but we never got so shitfaced
we couldn't make it back in.

256
00:28:19,459 --> 00:28:21,450
He's too good a sailor
to stay out there all night...

257
00:28:21,494 --> 00:28:22,791
and not let somebody know.

258
00:28:22,829 --> 00:28:25,662
-You sound like his wife.
-Just his friend.

259
00:28:25,698 --> 00:28:27,495
-You worry too much, Nick.
-Yeah.

260
00:28:30,236 --> 00:28:31,966
Where are we going?

261
00:28:32,005 --> 00:28:34,974
I'm going to talk Ashcroft
into taking out his boat...

262
00:28:35,008 --> 00:28:36,566
and looking for the ''Sea Grass.''

263
00:28:36,610 --> 00:28:38,077
Who's Ashcroft?

264
00:28:38,112 --> 00:28:40,080
Someone who owes me a favor.

265
00:28:40,114 --> 00:28:42,082
Can I come along?

266
00:28:42,116 --> 00:28:44,584
I thought you had to move on
to Vancouver?

267
00:28:44,618 --> 00:28:45,846
Eventually.

268
00:28:53,027 --> 00:28:55,291
The sheriff
will drive his own car.

269
00:28:55,330 --> 00:28:58,128
The mayor and his wife
are to be picked up at 6:45...

270
00:28:58,166 --> 00:29:00,157
and brought to the mayor's box.

271
00:29:00,201 --> 00:29:02,692
Then we will have speeches
by the mayor...

272
00:29:02,737 --> 00:29:04,602
the sheriff, and me.

273
00:29:04,639 --> 00:29:06,937
-Do you have my notes?
-Yes, ma'am.

274
00:29:06,975 --> 00:29:08,772
Then we will pass out
the candles...

275
00:29:08,810 --> 00:29:10,573
and begin the procession.

276
00:29:10,612 --> 00:29:13,514
Then I will go home
and pass out.

277
00:29:13,549 --> 00:29:15,744
I'm almost afraid to look.

278
00:29:15,784 --> 00:29:17,046
Well...

279
00:29:19,955 --> 00:29:21,923
Not bad. Not bad at all.

280
00:29:21,957 --> 00:29:23,788
A work of art.

281
00:29:23,826 --> 00:29:26,954
Sandy, just be civil to me
for another five hours.

282
00:29:26,996 --> 00:29:28,588
That's all I ask.

283
00:29:28,631 --> 00:29:30,098
Let's see now.

284
00:29:30,132 --> 00:29:31,929
The candles.
Did you order the candles?

285
00:29:31,967 --> 00:29:33,697
What a thought--a candlelight
procession with no candles.

286
00:29:33,737 --> 00:29:36,001
All taken care of.

287
00:29:36,039 --> 00:29:38,303
And the promotional material--
did you get that to Stevie?

288
00:29:38,341 --> 00:29:40,775
Signed, sealed, and delivered.

289
00:29:40,810 --> 00:29:43,574
Sandy, you can be a very
annoying person at times...

290
00:29:43,613 --> 00:29:44,978
but you do keep me together.

291
00:29:45,015 --> 00:29:47,006
Thank you, Mrs. Williams.

292
00:30:16,048 --> 00:30:20,144
...Spivey Point.
As of 1:57 today...

293
00:30:20,185 --> 00:30:22,085
the ''Sea Grass''
had not responded...

294
00:30:22,120 --> 00:30:24,020
to radio communication.

295
00:30:24,056 --> 00:30:26,081
The Coast Guard
has begun a sweep...

296
00:30:26,124 --> 00:30:27,819
south from Watley...

297
00:30:27,859 --> 00:30:29,486
around Arcom Reef...

298
00:30:29,528 --> 00:30:31,689
and should be
in the area of Spivey Point...

299
00:30:31,730 --> 00:30:34,199
in approximately one hour.

300
00:30:34,234 --> 00:30:37,533
Repeating this bulletin
from the Coast Guard...

301
00:30:37,570 --> 00:30:39,538
be on the look out
for the ''Sea Grass''...

302
00:30:39,572 --> 00:30:41,369
a thirty-foot trawler...

303
00:30:41,407 --> 00:30:45,844
last seen approximately 15 miles
east of Spivey Point.

304
00:30:45,878 --> 00:30:47,869
If you sight this vessel...

305
00:30:47,914 --> 00:30:50,610
please notify
the Coast Guard immediately.

306
00:31:01,795 --> 00:31:05,731
Nick, can I ask you a question?

307
00:31:05,766 --> 00:31:07,165
Is it always like this?

308
00:31:07,201 --> 00:31:10,170
It's always different.

309
00:31:10,204 --> 00:31:12,229
You're worried, aren't you?

310
00:31:12,273 --> 00:31:15,641
Yeah. She can get real mean.

311
00:31:15,677 --> 00:31:17,042
There.

312
00:31:28,323 --> 00:31:31,258
If I can just get through
the speeches without yawning.

313
00:31:31,293 --> 00:31:33,557
-I couldn't sleep last night.
-Too excited?

314
00:31:33,595 --> 00:31:36,087
No. Al went out on his boat
last night and didn't come home.

315
00:31:36,132 --> 00:31:38,692
-He still isn't back.
-Mrs. Williams!

316
00:31:38,734 --> 00:31:40,167
I called the Coast Guard,
and they said...

317
00:31:40,202 --> 00:31:42,329
''Oh, he might have had
engine trouble.''

318
00:31:42,371 --> 00:31:44,532
They said not to worry.

319
00:31:44,573 --> 00:31:46,200
He was complaining
about his boat last week.

320
00:31:46,242 --> 00:31:47,709
Maybe you ought to go home.

321
00:31:47,743 --> 00:31:50,234
That's the last place
I want to go.

322
00:31:50,279 --> 00:31:52,213
My dog started to bark
at 12:00 last night...

323
00:31:52,248 --> 00:31:54,217
and didn't stop
until 6:00 this morning.

324
00:31:54,251 --> 00:31:55,513
What happened?

325
00:31:55,552 --> 00:31:57,679
He was pointed toward the ocean
and growling.

326
00:31:57,721 --> 00:31:58,881
What does that tell you?

327
00:31:58,922 --> 00:32:01,322
My dog goes crazy and
decides to bark at the water.

328
00:32:01,358 --> 00:32:03,326
I heard the church bells
at midnight...

329
00:32:03,360 --> 00:32:05,157
as I started
to drift off to sleep...

330
00:32:05,195 --> 00:32:07,891
and my car alarm went off
for absolutely no reason.

331
00:32:07,931 --> 00:32:10,491
-Really?
-Woke up the whole block.

332
00:32:10,534 --> 00:32:13,230
This town sits around for
100 years and nothing happens...

333
00:32:13,270 --> 00:32:15,603
and then one night,
the whole place falls apart.

334
00:32:18,176 --> 00:32:20,906
Take this line, too.

335
00:32:20,945 --> 00:32:24,540
Al! Tommy! Dick!

336
00:32:29,220 --> 00:32:31,745
Cabin and steering house
are empty.

337
00:32:31,789 --> 00:32:34,053
Maybe somebody picked them up.

338
00:32:35,728 --> 00:32:37,525
There's water in the generator.

339
00:32:37,563 --> 00:32:39,724
But the deck is dry as a bone.

340
00:33:05,992 --> 00:33:08,119
There you have it.
My next project...

341
00:33:08,161 --> 00:33:10,994
restoration of
the Morgantown Road Cemetery.

342
00:33:11,030 --> 00:33:13,260
It's historical.
Our ancestors are buried here.

343
00:33:13,299 --> 00:33:15,996
-It'll cost a lot.
-Come on. So?

344
00:33:16,036 --> 00:33:17,833
This town should be proud
of its past.

345
00:33:17,872 --> 00:33:19,464
But trying to get
anyone involved...

346
00:33:19,507 --> 00:33:21,941
in community affairs
is like pulling teeth.

347
00:33:21,976 --> 00:33:23,170
Better get
the estimates ready...

348
00:33:23,210 --> 00:33:24,677
for the council meeting
next month.

349
00:33:24,712 --> 00:33:25,838
Yes, ma'am.

350
00:33:25,880 --> 00:33:27,347
Sandy, you're
the only person I know...

351
00:33:27,381 --> 00:33:29,679
who can make ''Yes, ma'am''
sound like ''Screw you.''

352
00:33:29,717 --> 00:33:30,979
Yes, ma'am.

353
00:33:31,018 --> 00:33:32,144
Now, if we'll just say
a little prayer...

354
00:33:32,186 --> 00:33:34,211
asking that
he not be in his cups.

355
00:33:40,662 --> 00:33:42,391
Not a good sign.

356
00:33:45,033 --> 00:33:47,627
Father Malone?

357
00:33:55,610 --> 00:33:57,909
Another bad sign.

358
00:33:57,947 --> 00:34:00,677
You try the study,
and I'll look up front.

359
00:34:24,775 --> 00:34:28,506
-Jesus!
-I'm sorry, Mrs. Williams.

360
00:34:28,545 --> 00:34:31,241
-Mrs. Williams--
-Are you all right?

361
00:34:31,281 --> 00:34:33,374
I have something to show you.

362
00:34:38,923 --> 00:34:41,391
''December 9.

363
00:34:41,426 --> 00:34:45,328
''Met with Blake this evening
for the first time.

364
00:34:45,363 --> 00:34:46,990
''He stood in the shadows...

365
00:34:47,031 --> 00:34:50,831
''to prevent me from getting
a clear look at his face.

366
00:34:50,869 --> 00:34:54,464
''What a vile disease this is.

367
00:34:54,506 --> 00:34:58,466
''He is a rich man
with a cursed condition...

368
00:34:58,511 --> 00:35:00,035
''but this does not
prevent him...

369
00:35:00,079 --> 00:35:02,138
''from trying to better
his situation...

370
00:35:02,181 --> 00:35:04,513
''and that of his comrades
at the colony.''

371
00:35:25,238 --> 00:35:27,763
Every single gauge is broken.

372
00:35:30,143 --> 00:35:32,668
-All the glass is shattered.
-Remind you of something?

373
00:35:32,712 --> 00:35:34,703
-Last night.
-Your truck.

374
00:35:42,857 --> 00:35:44,882
Thermometer's broken.

375
00:35:46,827 --> 00:35:49,387
The mercury's stuck
at twenty degrees.

376
00:35:50,865 --> 00:35:56,667
No water got in here,
but something awful cold did.

377
00:35:56,704 --> 00:36:00,835
''December 11.
Blake's proposition is simple.

378
00:36:00,876 --> 00:36:03,310
''He wants to move off
Tanzier Island...

379
00:36:03,345 --> 00:36:08,009
''and relocate the entire colony
just north of here.

380
00:36:08,050 --> 00:36:10,041
''He has purchased
a clipper ship...

381
00:36:10,085 --> 00:36:15,580
''called the 'Elizabeth Dane.'
with part of his fortune....

382
00:36:15,624 --> 00:36:19,425
''and asks only for permission
to settle here.

383
00:36:19,462 --> 00:36:22,659
''I must balance my feelings
of mercy and compassion...

384
00:36:22,699 --> 00:36:24,758
''toward this poor man...

385
00:36:24,801 --> 00:36:27,326
''with my revulsion
at the thought...

386
00:36:27,370 --> 00:36:30,806
''of a leper colony
only a mile distant.''

387
00:36:48,826 --> 00:36:51,021
It's rusted to the wall.

388
00:36:54,498 --> 00:36:55,931
It was on.

389
00:37:03,842 --> 00:37:05,810
They drank a lot of beer
last night.

390
00:37:05,844 --> 00:37:07,471
Every night.

391
00:37:07,512 --> 00:37:09,810
What's it like?

392
00:37:09,848 --> 00:37:12,817
It's always the same.
Room starts spinning--

393
00:37:12,851 --> 00:37:14,045
I mean fishing.

394
00:37:17,455 --> 00:37:18,649
You fish.

395
00:37:18,690 --> 00:37:20,318
The only thing I know
about fishing...

396
00:37:20,359 --> 00:37:21,690
is you use a lot of worms.

397
00:37:23,796 --> 00:37:25,161
Salt water.

398
00:37:27,466 --> 00:37:29,991
She was clean two nights ago.
I checked her out myself.

399
00:37:30,036 --> 00:37:33,369
Now it's as if she's been
turned over in the water.

400
00:37:35,541 --> 00:37:39,638
''April 20.
The six of us met tonight.

401
00:37:39,680 --> 00:37:41,648
''From midnight until 1:00...

402
00:37:41,682 --> 00:37:45,140
''we planned the death
of Blake and his comrades.

403
00:37:45,185 --> 00:37:47,847
''I tell myself
that Blake's gold...

404
00:37:47,888 --> 00:37:49,856
''will allow
the church to be built...

405
00:37:49,890 --> 00:37:52,586
''and our small settlement
to become a township...

406
00:37:52,626 --> 00:37:55,857
''but it does not soothe
the horror that I feel...

407
00:37:55,896 --> 00:37:59,560
''being an accomplice to murder.''

408
00:38:04,272 --> 00:38:06,069
Now what?

409
00:38:06,107 --> 00:38:08,166
Wait for the Coast Guard.

410
00:38:13,014 --> 00:38:15,005
I'm sorry.

411
00:38:15,049 --> 00:38:16,311
What for?

412
00:38:16,350 --> 00:38:19,342
Ever since you picked me up,
things have been going wrong.

413
00:38:19,387 --> 00:38:21,447
The clock broke, the windows
have been breaking...

414
00:38:21,490 --> 00:38:23,048
the weirdo at the door
last night.

415
00:38:23,092 --> 00:38:26,323
-That isn't you.
-I'm not so sure.

416
00:38:26,361 --> 00:38:29,159
Things seem to happen to me.

417
00:38:29,198 --> 00:38:30,529
I'm bad luck.

418
00:38:32,101 --> 00:38:36,731
I don't believe in luck,
good or bad.

419
00:38:36,772 --> 00:38:39,036
I don't believe
in anything much...

420
00:38:41,511 --> 00:38:44,036
Something did happen once.

421
00:38:46,382 --> 00:38:48,850
My father was a fisherman.

422
00:38:48,885 --> 00:38:53,345
He ran a trawler
out of Whitely Reef.

423
00:38:53,389 --> 00:38:57,723
One night, late,
he was coming back in.

424
00:38:57,761 --> 00:39:01,789
He was out beyond the reef,
out near Spivey Point.

425
00:39:01,832 --> 00:39:04,528
He looked to windward...

426
00:39:04,568 --> 00:39:08,060
and saw a brig
under shortsail...

427
00:39:08,105 --> 00:39:10,335
heading right for him.

428
00:39:12,843 --> 00:39:16,836
And he radioed.
There was no reply.

429
00:39:16,881 --> 00:39:21,478
Nothing moved on the deck,
but she held her course.

430
00:39:22,687 --> 00:39:25,850
My dad and two of his hands
boarded the brig--

431
00:39:25,891 --> 00:39:28,553
the ''Resa Jane.''

432
00:39:28,593 --> 00:39:31,994
No one was on board.

433
00:39:32,030 --> 00:39:33,998
There was food on the table...

434
00:39:34,032 --> 00:39:36,330
and a hot, steaming
cup of coffee.

435
00:39:36,368 --> 00:39:40,999
But underneath, the tin cup
was rusted to the table.

436
00:39:41,040 --> 00:39:44,441
And then something caught
my father's eye.

437
00:39:44,477 --> 00:39:50,973
It was a gold doubloon
minted in Spain, 1867.

438
00:39:51,017 --> 00:39:53,679
My dad picked up the coin,
put it in his breast pocket...

439
00:39:53,719 --> 00:39:56,017
of his jacket,
and zippered it up.

440
00:39:56,055 --> 00:39:59,855
He came home,
told us the story.

441
00:39:59,892 --> 00:40:04,489
And he unzippered the pocket
to give me the coin.

442
00:40:04,531 --> 00:40:06,055
It was gone.

443
00:40:08,402 --> 00:40:10,393
I think I'll go
to Vancouver now.

444
00:40:16,743 --> 00:40:20,509
''April 21st. The deed is done.

445
00:40:20,547 --> 00:40:23,210
''Blake followed
our false fire on shore...

446
00:40:23,251 --> 00:40:27,051
''and his ship broke apart
on the rocks off Spivey Point.

447
00:40:27,088 --> 00:40:29,648
''We were aided
by an unearthly fog...

448
00:40:29,691 --> 00:40:32,387
''that rolled in
as if heaven-sent...

449
00:40:32,427 --> 00:40:36,227
''although God had no part
in our actions tonight.

450
00:40:36,264 --> 00:40:38,562
''Blake's gold
will be recovered tomorrow...

451
00:40:38,600 --> 00:40:43,163
''but may the Lord forgive us
for what we have done.''

452
00:40:43,205 --> 00:40:46,106
I couldn't read any further.

453
00:40:47,443 --> 00:40:51,311
Your grandfather
had a way with words.

454
00:40:53,482 --> 00:40:57,077
Our celebration tonight
is a travesty.

455
00:40:57,119 --> 00:40:59,781
We're honoring murderers.

456
00:41:49,942 --> 00:41:53,400
Side one,
KAB promos and lead-ins.

457
00:41:53,445 --> 00:41:58,314
More music on
top of the world KAB 1340.

458
00:41:59,751 --> 00:42:02,049
Thirty-three.

459
